            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this Diophantine equation calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool focuses on
                <strong>linear Diophantine equations in two variables</strong>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">a·x + b·y = c</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                where <span class="font-mono">a</span>,
                <span class="font-mono">b</span>, and
                <span class="font-mono">c</span> are given integers and we seek
                <strong>integer solutions</strong>
                <span class="font-mono">(x, y)</span>.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Solvability condition</h3>
              <p>
                Let <span class="font-mono">d = gcd(a, b)</span>. A fundamental
                theorem of number theory says:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  a·x + b·y = c has integer solutions ⇔ d | c.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                If <span class="font-mono">d</span> does not divide
                <span class="font-mono">c</span>, the equation has
                <strong>no integer solutions</strong>. The calculator checks
                this first.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Finding one particular solution</h3>
              <p>
                If <span class="font-mono">d | c</span>, we use the
                <strong>extended Euclidean algorithm</strong> to find integers
                <span class="font-mono">u, v</span> such that:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">a·u + b·v = d.</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Multiplying both sides by
                <span class="font-mono">c / d</span> gives:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">a·(u·c/d) + b·(v·c/d) = c,</p>
              </div>
              <p>so a particular solution is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  x<sub>0</sub> = u·(c/d), &nbsp; y<sub>0</sub> = v·(c/d).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. General integer solution</h3>
              <p>
                Once we have one solution
                <span class="font-mono">(x<sub>0</sub>, y<sub>0</sub>)</span>,
                all integer solutions are given by:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  x = x<sub>0</sub> + (b/d)·t<br />
                  y = y<sub>0</sub> − (a/d)·t
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                where <span class="font-mono">t</span> is any integer (… −2, −1,
                0, 1, 2, …). The calculator displays this parametric form and
                also generates a few sample solutions for consecutive values of
                <span class="font-mono">t</span>.
              </p>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>Consider the equation:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">15x + 21y = 6</p>
              </div>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Compute d = gcd(15, 21)</strong><br />
                  Using Euclid's algorithm:
                  <span class="font-mono text-sm"
                    >21 = 1·15 + 6, 15 = 2·6 + 3, 6 = 2·3 + 0</span
                  >, so <span class="font-mono">d = 3</span>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check solvability</strong><br />
                  <span class="font-mono">3 | 6</span>, so solutions exist.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Find u, v with 15u + 21v = 3</strong> (extended
                  Euclidean algorithm). One result is
                  <span class="font-mono">u = -4, v = 3</span>, so:
                  <span class="font-mono">15(−4) + 21·3 = −60 + 63 = 3</span>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Scale to get a particular solution</strong><br />
                  <span class="font-mono">c/d = 6/3 = 2</span>, so:
                  <span class="font-mono">x<sub>0</sub> = −4·2 = −8</span>,
                  <span class="font-mono">y<sub>0</sub> = 3·2 = 6</span>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Write the general solution</strong><br />
                  Here <span class="font-mono">b/d = 21/3 = 7</span>,
                  <span class="font-mono">a/d = 15/3 = 5</span>, so:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                      x = −8 + 7t<br />
                      y = 6 − 5t, &nbsp; t ∈ ℤ.
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Typical use cases</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>Number theory and abstract algebra homework.</li>
                <li>
                  Cryptography (e.g., modular inverses and key schedules).
                </li>
                <li>Competitive programming and algorithmic problems.</li>
                <li>
                  Diophantine analysis in combinatorics and discrete math.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations of this calculator</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is intentionally focused on
                <strong>linear</strong> equations in two variables. More general
                Diophantine problems include:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Higher-degree equations like
                  <span class="font-mono">x² + y² = z²</span> or
                  <span class="font-mono">x³ + y³ + z³ = k</span>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Systems of several linear equations in several variables.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Exponential Diophantine equations such as
                  <span class="font-mono">2ˣ − 3ʸ = 1</span>.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These usually require more specialized theory (e.g., lattice
                methods, modular arithmetic, or deep results like the
                Thue–Siegel–Roth theorem) and are beyond the scope of this
                simple solver.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>What is a Diophantine equation?</h3>
              <p>
                A Diophantine equation is an equation where the unknowns are
                required to be integers. The name comes from Diophantus of
                Alexandria, a Greek mathematician who studied such problems.
                Linear Diophantine equations are the simplest and most widely
                used class.
              </p>

              <h3>Why are Diophantine equations important?</h3>
              <p>
                Diophantine equations appear in number theory, cryptography,
                coding theory, combinatorics, and even in practical problems
                like scheduling and resource allocation where only whole units
                make sense.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I restrict x or y to be non-negative?</h3>
              <p>
                The general solution describes <em>all</em> integer solutions.
                If you need additional constraints such as
                <span class="font-mono">x ≥ 0</span> or
                <span class="font-mono">y ≥ 0</span>, you can plug the
                parametric formulas for <span class="font-mono">x(t)</span> and
                <span class="font-mono">y(t)</span> into those inequalities and
                solve for the allowed range of <span class="font-mono">t</span>.
              </p>

              <h3>
                How is this different from solving a linear equation over the
                reals?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Over the real numbers, any equation
                <span class="font-mono">a·x + b·y = c</span> with
                <span class="font-mono">(a, b) ≠ (0, 0)</span> has infinitely
                many solutions. Over the integers, the divisibility condition
                <span class="font-mono">gcd(a, b) | c</span> becomes crucial,
                and the structure of the solution set is discrete rather than
                continuous.
              </p>
